**1\) Executive Summary — What we’re building and why**

We are building the *Yale Newcomer Survival Guide* \- a role-aware, searchable web hub that consolidates practical, student-vetted guidance for life in New Haven (housing, transportation, food, academics, groceries, entertainment, athletics). Today, newcomers stitch answers from Reddit, WhatsApp, and scattered websites; quality is inconsistent and hard to verify. Our platform centralizes curated posts and authoritative links, letting users quickly search, and  browse by category, while returning students contribute updates that an admin reviews for accuracy.

The product serves three clear roles: **Reader**, **Contributor** (submit and edit posts), and **Admin** (approve/reject, manage taxonomy, ensure freshness). The MVP \- intentionally lightweight and feasible within one semester \- includes Django built-in authentication with groups, category-based content, site-wide search (posts \+ vetted links), a submission → pending → approval workflow, local image, and  uploads. We deliberately exclude high-cost features (comments, upvotes, real-time, maps, social login) to control scope and deliver a robust, reliable core.

Success for Sprint 1 sets up a production-ready path for Sprint 2: users can log in, find answers in minutes, and return to saved content; contributors can publish through a clean review flow; admins can moderate efficiently. We will measure adoption and value via active users, search engagement, time-to-publish (≤48h), and content volume/freshness across categories, ensuring the guide remains accurate, fast, and genuinely useful to each incoming cohort.

### **3\) MVP Scope**

A web platform built with Django where users can log in, browse categorized content, search curated posts and trusted links, and submit posts for admin approval. Admins manage pending posts through a simple dashboard.

*Key features:*

1. Role-based login (Reader, Contributor, Admin).  
2. Category hub and site-wide search.  
3. Contributor submission → pending → approval → live workflow.  
4. Clean Bootstrap UI; local image upload; Markdown/TinyMCE editor.

*Success Metrics:*

1. ≥10 users in first month; ≥60% search engagement.  
2. Median publish time ≤48 hours.  
3. ≥30 approved posts across categories by semester’s end.

# **5\) Technical Architecture**

*Framework*

* Django 5 (Python) \+ Django Templates  
  * Server-rendered HTML, minimal JS, built-in auth/groups for Reader/Contributor/Admin, Django Admin for moderation UI.

*Database*

* DuckDB via Python `duckdb` client (service layer) or `django-duckdb` backend`.`  
  * Tables: `categories`, `posts` (status: draft/pending/approved/rejected), `bookmarks`, `external_links`.  
  * Simple indexes on `posts(status)`, `posts(category_id)`, `posts(updated_at)`.

*Deployment*

* Single-container deploy on Render (or [Fly.io](http://Fly.io)):  
  * Dockerfile builds Django app.  
  * Env vars: `DJANGO_SECRET_KEY`, `DUCKDB_PATH`, `DEBUG`.  
* Dev loop: feature branches → AI-assisted IDE(Cursor) for scaffolding/tests → PR → GitHub Actions (lint, `pytest`, `manage.py check`) → auto deploy to staging → prod promote.

*General rationale*

This stack optimizes speed-to-MVP with low ops: Django gives us auth, forms, and admin out of the box; DuckDB keeps data portable and zero-maintenance (a single file) while still allowing fast SQL and future analytics; a single-container deploy keeps the site easy to run anywhere and simple to scale later or swap to Postgres if needed.
